327 E. 12 St. Apr 5, 70?
My dear little sister;
I wrote you a few lines on Sabbath when I suppose you were having a pretty rough time.  Hope you are about at your journey's end now.  Wonder how you feel on landing.  Sunday P.M. I felt so uneasy about you whenever the wind blew and the rain poured that I went to see our good Dr.? K had quite a long visit.  He went to see how you were getting along.  Said the see was pretty rough but you wre all safe.  You were lying down had been trying ot read but could not make much of it.

Mon. 6 P.M. June 12
My dear little Sister;
I mailed you a letter early this morn but much send you another post haste with medicine for your cold. I have been feeling uneasy about your thin clothing, especially today as it is quite cool. Cant you buy a flannel wrapper to put on? Get some canton flannel and make you a pair of drawers. Your linen dress will be cool to travel in. Mr. & Mrs. Warren did not call, so it would have availed nothing if we had

Monday morn Apr 7, 1856
Dear Ma;
Recieved your letters Sat. eve. Thank you for that piece. It is I think sufficient Having an opportunity to send a line this morning, and the roads getting so bad, that we dont know when another will offer, I thought I would write a few words to say that R. still improves. Had a first rate day yesterday, is very well this morn. His crisis continues, boils and diarhea, I am doing very well. love to all. Mary.

Graefenbery, May 8, 1857
My dear Mother; 
the date of this reminds me that you are now sixty-years of age. Dear Mother, is it not time for you to begin to rest more? I think of you often and wish I could be of more comfort to you and Father now in your declining years. Your good kind letter was gratefully recieved. It gives us great pleasure to feel that we are remembered by the loved ones at home. You will I know I rejoice with when I tell you that I have had those other bad teeth extracted, roots I mean, and you cannot feel what a relief it is
